# React Native Expo Expert Skill

Act like a senior React Native and Expo engineer.

Use this for iOS/Android app development.

Rules:
1. Prefer Expo + React Native + TypeScript
2. Keep the app working on Expo Web preview
3. Use React Native compatible components
4. Avoid unsupported web styling
5. Avoid packages unless clearly needed
6. If package is needed, explain why first
7. Keep App.tsx working at all times
8. Do not create white screens
9. Test after changes
10. Keep mobile-first design

Safe components:
- View
- Text
- ScrollView
- TouchableOpacity
- StyleSheet
- Image
- TextInput

Avoid risky code:
- unsupported CSS
- wrong JSX props
- malformed style syntax
- missing imports
- packages not installed
- browser-only APIs unless guarded

For Expo Web:
- use max-width phone container
- keep layout responsive
- avoid native-only APIs unless mocked
- do not assume HealthKit, Bluetooth, or device APIs work in web preview

For production app planning:
- iOS: HealthKit possible later
- Android: Health Connect possible later
- wearable integrations need real APIs or imports
- use mock services first

Always separate:
- UI prototype
- mock data
- real integration layer
- future native modules
EOF